544":"1544","1540":"1540","1639":"1639","1505":"1505","Kelby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kelby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","North Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"North Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Keelby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Keelby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Southe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably an altered form of German   Sauter   or of its variant <b>Sauther</b>.","English (London): perhaps a variant of   Souter  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Southers","meanings":["English: apparently a variant of   Souther  ."]},{"name":"Sauter","meanings":["German: occupational name for a shoemaker or cobbler (one who sews leather and other materials), Middle High German <i>sūter</i> (from Latin <i>sutor</i>, an agent derivative of <i>suere</i> ‘to sew’). Compare   Sauder   and   Souter  .","English (Kent): variant of   Salter  .","Dutch and Flemish: occupational name for a producer or seller of salt, from an agent derivative of Middle Dutch <i>sout</i> ‘salt’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir George Southe was born in 1500, his father, John South, was 20 and his mother, Mary South, was 20. He had at least 5 sons with Jane Grace Danby. He died in 1578, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1500–1578":"1500–1578","1505–1582":"1505–1582","1544–1591":"1544–1591","1545–1639":"1545–1639","1546–1591":"1546–1591","1547–1591":"1547–1591","–1580":"–1580","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1582":"1582","1580":"1580","1591":"1591","1480":"1480","1547":"1547","1546":"1546","1545":"1545","1578":"1578","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1540":"1540","1639":"1639","1505":"1505","Kelby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kelby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"North Kesteven, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Keelby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Keelby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1500–1578":"1500–1578","1505–1582":"1505–1582","1544–1591":"1544–1591","1545–1639":"1545–1639","1546–1591":"1546–1591","1547–1591":"1547–1591","–1580":"–1580","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1582":"1582","1580":"1580","1591":"1591","1480":"1480","1547":"1547","1546":"1546","1545":"1545","1578":"1578","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1540":"1540","1639":"1639","1505":"1505","Kelby, Linco